{
  "text": "Obesity is a major public health problem associated with numerous morbidities [CITATION_1] . Body mass index (BMI), the basis for the assessment of obesity, has been shown to be a risk factor for colorectal cancer incidence and death [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . It was recognized that higher BMI was associated with increased technical difficulties and postoperative morbidity during colorectal surgery [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . In contrast, other studies reported no negative impact of obesity on surgical outcome after rectal surgery [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
